[normal]R&amp;D expenditure [bold]has a key role to play in[bold] [bold]g[bold]rowth and [bold]r[bold]ebalancing[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Progress[bold] has been made[bold] [bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Nonetheless, the UK lags behind its competitors when it comes to inno[bold]vation[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]UK BERD has not kept pace with the [bold]OECD average[bold]BERD as a % GDP
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The decline in BERD as a proportion of GDP was [bold]not intensified by the recession[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Manufacturers conduct the lion’s share of BERD[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There are signs that manufacturers have the appetite to [bold]ste[bold]p up investment in R&amp;D[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]C[bold]ompanies say key con[bold]cerns are[bold] speed to market, turning innovations into market opp[bold]ortunity and technical barriers[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]T
[normal]urning an innovation into market opportunity can be difficult for a number of reasons. For example, customers are not always keen to be the first mover when it comes to buying a new and relatively unknown product. Another issue can be that sales people nee
[normal]d to learn how to sell new products or services, and this can take time. These challenges in turning innovation into market opportunities are a particular issue given that manufacturers expect to use innovation to develop new markets. 
